<font color="#FF0000">AGENT ORANGE ISSUE IS NOT DEAD</font><br>
<tt>Fri Oct  3 23:15:41 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
<br>
Most all Vietnam vets were exposed in some manner at some time through, contact, food, water, or inhalation.  I too like many others was exposed and have been ill for many many years.  I have been diagnosed with Lupus back some years ago.  I don't know what to believe that I have all I know is I was exposed, I am ill and my wife and I lost a son to severe birth defects.   I do know Agent Orange is a killer.  I also know that the settlement of the AO lawsuit was a joke as far as guidelines for disbursement.  The settlement disbursement guidelines do nothing as far as I know, for the vet who can still work and works while being ill.  The guidelines do nothing to compensate for the loss of a child.  The scientific community will never agree, but isn't it so very interesting that medical problems we have been complaining of, and I beat the drum about in the late 70's early 80's,  are recognized now in the late 90's.  We as vets complained to the VA and Congress about Spina Bifida in our children, back in the 70's.  I say, stop the scientific chest beating as to what it will or won't or couldn't cause and get on with health care and compensation through forthright acceptance.  11th Armored Cavalry, 1st Sqdn, C-Trp, 69-70.
<p><code>-- HogsOnly@aol.com  (Chris Johnson) </code><p>


